{A very welcome to this course! In this course, I present to you a complete repertoire for Black based on the Semi-Slav defense. As usual, I stick to my principle of opting for rare/unexplored directions. This repertoire can be played universally. You can play this against both higher-rated and lower-rated, as the positions remain dynamic yet objectively balanced. Let me take you through the major directions of the course.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 c6 {the starting of the Semi-Slav. We can also reach this position via 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Nf3 d5 4.Nc3 c6 or 1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 e6 move order. While White has many choices here, the critical ones seem to be 5.Bg5, 5.e3 & 5.g3.} 5. Bg5 {The most ambitious move from a strategic viewpoint. White brings their bishop out to the most active square.} (5. e3 {This is known as the 'Meran' variation. They play conservatively and defend the pawn on c4. While there are several sub-systems in the Meran branch, I recommend a consistent setup for Black throughout the system.} Nbd7 {we bring our knight out nevertheless. Typically, Black brings their bishop out to d6. However, the setup I recommend is ...Nbd7-Be7 followed by playing 0-0 & ...b6 interchangeably based on White's response.} 6. Bd3 (6. Be2 Be7 {also leads to positions similar to the lines with 6...Be7.}) 6... Be7 {The bishop is less actively placed on e7 than on d6. However, the advantage of having the bishop on e7 is that after e4 dxe4 Nxe4, the bishop on e7 isn't attacked! (unlike it would have been on d6). The critical branching point arises after} 7. O-O O-O 8. Qc2 b6 9. b3 Bb7 10. Bb2 h6 $5 {which reduces the effect of White's Ne5. The reason why I like this particular setup is because it is easy to remember but more importantly, White has to show restraint as their intended solution e4 often leads to worse positions for White. I think this is a perfect weapon to play against any player as the lines are extremely strategic.}) (5. g3 {Against this, I recommend} Nbd7 6. Bg2 dxc4 7. O-O Be7 8. e4 O-O {and here, White has two major possibilities.} 9. a4 {They play this to prevent ...b5.} (9. Bf4 {The more ambitious response. They ignore our threats and prioritize their development. Instead of the usual moves like ...Re8 or ...b5, I recommend the novel} b6 $5 {which solves Black's opening problems quite easily.}) 9... b5 $5 {we still play it out nevertheless. Black might also be a pawn, but they are to control all of the light squares after a couple of moves. Analysis shows that the position remains double-edged, with all three results being possible.}) ({sidelines like} 5. Qb3) (5. Qd3) (5. a3) (5. Bd2) (5. Qc2 {are covered in the final chapter.}) (5. cxd5 {the trendy} exd5 {is covered exhaustively in the 13th chapter. My analysis show that we have nothing to worry here.}) 5... h6 {going for the 'Moscow' system.} 6. Bh4 {The 'Anti-Moscow' variation. This move allows us to sharpen up the position with} (6. Bxf6 {The Moscow variation.} Qxf6 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7] we stick to the ...g6 setups here.} 7. e3 ({against the rare} 7. Qb3 {I recommend the fresh} Qe7 $5 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Ge8g8,Gb8d7,Gd5c4,Ye6e5,Yb7b6,Yc8b7,Yc6c5] preparing to play ...Qb4 in some variations. Typically, we play the usual ...g6-Nbd7-0-0 setup.}) ({sidelines like} 7. Qc2) (7. g3 {and}) (7. a3 {are covered too.}) 7... g6 8. Bd3 Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. e4 {here, instead of the usual ...dxe4, I recommend playing} Qd8 {[%cal Gc6c5] with the intention of striking the center with ...c5 next. While the position remains objectively equal, Black often obtains a long-term strategic advantage thanks to the pair of bishops/}) 6... dxc4 7. e4 g5 8. Bg3 b5 {Although our position is a bit extended, a pawn's a pawn.} 9. Be2 {here, I recommend the rare} Nbd7 {and after the most played move} 10. O-O {instead of transposing to the main lines with ...Bb7, I recommend the extremely rare} ({options like} 10. d5) (10. h4) (10. Ne5) (10. Qc2 {are covered deeply as well.}) 10... b4 11. Na4 Nxe4 {going for the pawn. My analysis shows that the position remains double-edged. I tried playing this position out without an engine against a 2650+ Grandmaster, and he struggled to even equalize as White!} *

