{[%evp 0,44,18,19,35,7,39,31,52,5,34,11,33,-24,2,2,-9,-2,-2,-18,-14,-40,-41,-58,-67,-21,-28,-27,-3,-6,-4,-29,6,-27,-42,-15,-15,-78,-51,-32,-37,-22,9,-35,54,18,35] Welcome to the first chapter. In this chapter, we will begin the coverage of the absolute main line of the 5.Bg5 h6 6.Bh4 dxc4 system.} 1. d4 d5 (1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c6 {This can be another way of reaching the Semi-Slav.}) 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 {[%cal Gd5c4,Rb7b5] The starting point of Semi-Slav. Black threatens ...dxc4-b5.} 5. Bg5 {One of the two major moves in the position. White brings their bishop out to the most active square.} h6 {we kick their bishop away. Our idea is to meet Bh4 with ...dxc4 followed by...g5. This way, we'll avoid the Botvinnik variation arising with an early e4-e5.} ({starting out with} 5... dxc4 {is also possible.} 6. e4 b5 7. e5 {[%cal Rh7h6,Rg7g5,Gg5h4,Rf3g5] This leads to the Botvinik variation. ...h6-g5 can be now met with Bh4 & Nxg5. While this remains a plausible direction, White seems to generally keep an easier game here.}) 6. Bh4 {The most ambitious move. They maintain their bishop.} dxc4 {time to be greedy!} 7. e4 {White gains space in the center. They threaten Bxc4/e5.} g5 {we take away the chance from White to pin our knight on f6.} 8. Bg3 b5 {an important point in the position. Black wants to latch onto the extra pawn they have. In return, White keeps a lead in development and somewhat more active pieces. This is referred to as the 'Anti-Moscow' Gambit.} 9. Be2 {Their main move in the position. White prepares 0-0.} ({other moves like} 9. Ne5 {or}) (9. h4 {are covered in subsequent chapters.}) {here, instead of the usual 9...Bb7, I recommend the rare} 9... Nbd7 {[%cal Rd7e5] covering the e5-square. This move is aimed to prevent White's option of playing Ne5. Usually, when Black plays an early ...Nbd7, the d4-d5 break can be challenging for them. However, for us, 10.d5 isn't super challenging.} 10. O-O {The most logical response. They tuck their king in.} ({moves like} 10. d5 {are covered in the subsequent chapters.}) 10... b4 $5 {This rare has not been employed in any top-level encounter except Inarkiev-Dreev back in 2007! We decide to be greedy and look to grab their central e4-pawn.} 11. Na4 Nxe4 {[%cal Ge4g3,Gf8g7,Ge8g8] Black grabs the second pawn. We want to take on g3, play ...Bg7 & ...0-0 next.} 12. Be5 $5 {a sophisticated move. They stop us from playing ...Bg7.} (12. Bxc4 {this allows Black to execute their plans.} Nxg3 13. hxg3 Bg7 {[%cal Rc6c5,Re6e5] we'll look to break open with ...c5 or ...e5 at some point.} 14. Re1 O-O 15. Rc1 Bb7 16. Bd3 (16. Bb3 Qe7 $11 {doesn't change much.}) 16... Qe7 $15 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4][%cal Ga8c8,Gf8d8,Rc6c5,Gg7b2] Black keeps a small edge due to the pair of bishops and a better pawn structure. As described earlier, we would like to open up the board with ...c5 or ...e5. Even if they land a piece on c5, we don't particularly mind it as they have weaknesses along the h8-a1 diagonal.}) (12. Re1 $6 {This leads to a better version of the 12.Bxc4 lines for Black. After} Nxg3 13. hxg3 Bg7 $15 {we are better.}) 12... Nef6 {[%cal Gd7e5,Rf8d6] we couldn't have given up the castling rights. Black threatens ...Nxe5/...g4.} 13. Rc1 {The most played move. White brings their lookout to attack c4.} (13. Nc5 $6 {can be met with} Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxc5 15. dxc5 Qd5 $15 {Black either improves their structure or wins the c5-pawn. We'll manage to castle comfortably as well.}) (13. Nd2 $6 {going for the c5-pawn isn't the right strategy.} Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nd5 15. Nxc4 Be7 {[%cal Ge7d6] keeping the d6-square guarded.} 16. g3 Kf8 $15 {[%cal Gf8g7,Rc8a6] Black castles artificially, keeping the h6-pawn guarded. We'll play ...Ba6 next. We keep an edge due to their misplaced knights and our advantage over the bishop pair.}) (13. Qc2 $6 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nd7 15. Qxc4 (15. Rad1 Qe7 16. Qxc4 c5 $15 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8,Gc8b7,Gb7f3,Gd7e5] also keeps an edge.}) 15... c5 $17 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gc8b7,Gb7f3,Yb7d5,Yg5g4,Rc4c2] White will face issues with their e5-pawn.}) (13. Bxc4 {One of the two good for White.} g4 {trying to deflect their knight away from the e5-square.} 14. Nd2 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nd7 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gd7e5]} 16. Re1 Qc7 {sooner or later, they'll lose the e5-pawn.} 17. Ne4 (17. Qxg4 {can be met with} Nxe5 18. Qf4 Bd6 $132 {[%csl Gd6,Rh2][%cal Ge5g6,Rd6h2] our dark-squared bishop is unchallenged. Note that} 19. Qf6 $6 {is weak. After} (19. g3 {can be met with} c5 $132 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7h1] with a sharp position OTB.}) 19... Rg8 $17 {[%csl Rc4,Rh2][%cal Gg8g6,Ge5g4,Ye5d7] It is Black who's on top. We are exerting threats on the Kingside.}) 17... Nxe5 (17... Qxe5 18. Qxg4 {with our king in the center and the knights on the board, this can be disastrous.}) 18. Nf6+ Ke7 19. Nxg4 Bg7 {[%csl Gc7,Ge7,Gg7] Although we have lost castling privileges, we have developed with a couple of tempos. Our king remains quite safe on e7. The g7-bishop is unchallenged.} 20. Qe2 (20. Nxe5 Bxe5 $132 {[%csl Gd4,Rf2,Rh2][%cal Ge5h2,Ge5d4,Gc6c5,Gd4g1]}) 20... Nxc4 {our bishop pair would be monstrous in these positions.} 21. Qxc4 Rd8 {[%cal Ge7f8,Gf8g8] looking to tuck the king in.} 22. Qxb4+ c5 $1 {taking advantage of the fact that they can't trade queens.} (22... Ke8 $5 {also keeps balance.}) 23. Nxc5 Rb8 24. Qa3 Bxb2 $11 {White needs to be careful in order to equalize here.}) 13... Nxe5 {an extremely rare move.} 14. Nxe5 Bd6 {Black's point. We are willing to give c6 away.} 15. Qe1 {the top choice of engines. White avoids a queen trade.} ({If they grab the c4-pawn with} 15. Nxc4 {we can comfortably play} O-O {Black is out of the woods here.} 16. Nxd6 Qxd6 17. Bf3 Rd8 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd6d4] counterattack! It is quite important not to be passive in these lines.} 18. Qe2 (18. Rxc6 Qxd4 $15) 18... Qf4 $132) (15. Nxc6 {quite logical.} Qc7 16. Ne5 $5 (16. Rxc4 Ba6 17. Rc2 Bxe2 18. Qxe2 O-O $11 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Yc7d7,Yc7b7,Gf8c8,Gf6d5] also offers easy play to Black.}) 16... Bxe5 17. dxe5 Qxe5 18. Bf3 Rb8 19. Rxc4 O-O $11 {Black has managed to solve their opening problems while keeping an extra pawn.}) (15. Bf3 $6 Bxe5 $1 16. dxe5 (16. Bxc6+ $4 Bd7 17. Bxa8 Bf4 $19 {[%csl Ra4,Ra8,Rc1][%cal Gd8a8,Gd7a4,Gf4c1] we win material.}) 16... Qxd1 17. Rfxd1 Nd5 18. Rxc4 Ba6 $15 {[%cal Ga6b5,Ga7a5] offers easy play to Black.}) (15. f4 {trying to open up the Kingside. This favours Black due to concrete problems..} gxf4 16. Rxf4 (16. Bf3 $6 {dubious, but interesting.} Bxe5 17. Bxc6+ {White's point.} (17. dxe5 Nd5 $17 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gc8a6] offers Black a great game.}) 17... Bd7 18. Bxa8 Qxa8 19. dxe5 {we have lost material but after} Rg8 20. Qe2 Nd5 $19 {[%csl Ra4,Rg2][%cal Gd7a4,Gd5e3,Gg8g2] Black's attack is decisive!}) (16. Nxc6 Qd7 17. Ne5 Bxe5 18. dxe5 Qxd1 19. Rfxd1 Nd7 $11 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gd7e5] the e5-pawn will be lost.}) 16... Bxe5 17. dxe5 Qxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Nd5 $15 {[%cal Gd5e3,Ge8e7] we end up keeping an extra pawn.}) (15. Rxc4 Bxe5 {we begin our liquidation spree...} 16. dxe5 Qxd1 17. Rxd1 Nd5 18. Rxc6 {White has the material back but after} Bb7 19. Rcc1 O-O {It is Black who keeps some minute pressure in the endgame.} 20. Nc5 {It seems we are under pressure but after} (20. Bf3 Rac8 21. Nc5 Ba8 $11 {[%csl Rb2,Gd5,Re5][%cal Gc8c7,Gf8c8] we would to double on the c-file next.}) 20... Nf4 $1 21. Bf1 Bd5 {It is White who needs to be a bit careful here.}) (15. Bxc4 {can be met with} Bxe5 16. dxe5 Qxd1 17. Rfxd1 Nd7 18. Re1 Ke7 $17 {They don't have sufficient compensation after the queens come off.}) 15... Nd7 $1 {an important move to remember!} (15... Bxe5 16. dxe5 Nd5 17. Bxc4 $14) 16. Bxc4 {[%cal Ge5f7] the strongest response.} (16. Nxc4 {can be met with} Be7 (16... Nb6 $5 $11) 17. Bf3 O-O {[%cal Gc8a6,Ga8b8] we have managed to develop with ease while keeping the bishop pair.}) (16. f4 $6 gxf4 17. Nxc4 Nb6 {exchanging pieces off now that we have won another pawn.} 18. Naxb6 axb6 $15 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Ga8a2,Ge8g8]}) (16. Nxc6 Qf6 17. Bxc4 O-O $11 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ga7a5] Our kingside problems are solved completely.}) 16... Bxe5 17. dxe5 Qa5 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ga5e5] the pawn on e5 is lost!} 18. Qd1 {stopping us from castling.} (18. b3 Nxe5 19. Be2 {[%cal Gc1c5]} O-O {they keep compensation for the lost pawns, but nothing more.} 20. Rc5 Qc7 21. Qxb4 Nd7 22. Rc2 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6d5,Gc7e5] with ...Rd8-Qe5 or ...Nd5 coming up next.}) 18... Bb7 {[%cal Ge8c8] threatening ...0-0-0!} (18... Qxe5 $6 19. Re1 Qc7 20. Bxe6 $5 $16) (18... Nxe5 19. Qd6 $1 $18) 19. Qb3 {[%cal Ga2a3]} O-O-O (19... Ke7 $5 {is interesting too.}) 20. a3 bxa3 21. bxa3 Kb8 {[%cal Gb8a8,Gd8b8] Black prepares ...Ka8.} 22. Rb1 {this looks dangerous but after} Nb6 $11 {followed by the queen trade, it is only Black that can be better in the endgame.} *

