{In the second chapter, we'll be covering White's alternatives on the 10th move in the absolute main line of the Semi-Slav.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 dxc4 7. e4 g5 8. Bg3 b5 9. Be2 Nbd7 {the starting point of this chapter.} 10. Ne5 $5 {while this is certainly playable, it isn't dangerous for Black anymore.} (10. h4 {White wants to go provoke ...g4 so that they can play Ne5.} b4 $5 {staying consistent with our play.} (10... g4 11. Ne5 Bb7 {leads to a main line arising after 9...Bb7 10.h4 g4 11.Ne5 Nbd7.}) 11. Na4 Nxe4 {Black grabs the second pawn.} 12. Be5 {The same plan. White doesn't us to play ...Bg7 & ...0-0.} (12. hxg5 $6 Nxg3 13. fxg3 Qc7 $15) 12... Rg8 {[%cal Gg5g4]} (12... Nef6 {doesn't work anymore due to} 13. hxg5 $16) 13. Qc2 Nef6 (13... g4 $5 {deserves attention as well.}) 14. hxg5 (14. Bxc4 Bb7 {[%cal Gg5g4,Rc6c5] if they don't take on g5, we'll play ...g4 & ...c5.}) 14... hxg5 15. Bxc4 Bb7 16. O-O-O $5 {safeguarding the king.} g4 {deflecting the knight away from e5.} 17. Ne1 Nxe5 18. dxe5 Nd5 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gd8a5,Ye8c8,Yd8g5] It is White who needs to be careful here. Their pawn on e5 is vulnerable and their pieces are inactive.}) (10. Qc2 {[%cal Ge1c1] preparing 0-0-0 while guarding the pawn on e4.} Nh5 {we stick with our plan of threatening their dark-squared bishop.} 11. O-O-O {the most consistent.} (11. d5 {also makes sense.} Nxg3 12. hxg3 cxd5 13. exd5 exd5 14. O-O-O $5 {Initiative>Material!} (14. Nxd5 {this doesn't scare us. After} Bg7 $15 {[%cal Gg7b2,Ge8g8] our bishop is unchallenged. We'll castle next.}) 14... Nb6 (14... Bg7 15. Rxd5 {[%csl Rb5,Rc4][%cal Gd5b5] can be a bit problematic.}) 15. Rhe1 {It seems like Black's under pressure from all sides but after} Bg7 16. Bxc4+ Be6 17. Bxb5+ Kf8 $11 {[%csl Rc1,Rc3][%cal Gg7a1,Ga8c8,Gc8c1] We keep material balance, and our king remains safe; we can generate play down the c-file.}) (11. Rd1 g4 $1 12. Nd2 Qb6 $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb6d4]}) 11... g4 $1 {we start our counterplay!} 12. Nd2 (12. Bh4 Be7 {can lead to scary positions for White.} 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Ne1 Nf4 $15) 12... Rg8 {[%cal Gc8b7,Rd8a5] we want to play ...Bb7-Qb6/Qa5 & ...0-0-0 next.} 13. e5 {[%cal Gd2e4]} Bb7 14. Nde4 Nxg3 15. hxg3 Qa5 $15 {[%cal Ge8c8] our king would remain safe on c8. White doesn't have sufficient compensation.}) (10. e5 Nh5 {doesn't help White. Black will play ...Bb7 next. We can take on g3 anytime we want.} 11. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2e4] played in all OTB games.} Nxg3 12. hxg3 Qb6 13. Nde4 Bb7 $15 {[%csl Rd4,Re5][%cal Ge8c8,Rc6c5,Gb7h1] we'll castle long or play ...c5.}) (10. d5 {going for an immediate confrontation in the center.} cxd5 11. exd5 b4 {forcing them to release the tension.} 12. dxe6 {played in all games to date.} (12. Nb5 Nxd5 13. Bxc4 N7b6 $13 {offers Black a comfortable game. White keeps compensation of course, but the position remains complex.}) 12... bxc3 13. exd7+ Bxd7 14. bxc3 Bg7 15. Bxc4 O-O {with our king away from danger, Black isn't under pressure anymore.} 16. O-O Ne4 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Ge4c3] this move ensures that we'll recover the pawn.} 17. Be5 Bg4 18. Re1 Qxd1 19. Raxd1 Bxf3 $11 {The c3-pawn is now lost. Black equalizes completely.}) 10... Bg7 {continuing to delay ...Bb7.} 11. O-O {White gets their king to safety.} (11. Nxc6 {recapturing the pawn gives Black easy play.} Qb6 12. d5 (12. Ne5 $6 {can be met with} Bb7 13. Qc2 O-O 14. O-O Rad8 {[%cal Gd7e5,Gb5b4,Gb6d4] It is Black who's exerting threats here...}) 12... Nc5 {[%cal Gc5e4] our moves are flowing here...} 13. Qd4 Bb7 14. Be5 {among the many equalizers that Black has, I prefer} Ncd7 15. Qxb6 axb6 16. Nxb5 (16. Bd4 O-O 17. Nxb5 Nxe4 $11) 16... Nxe5 17. Nxe5 exd5 18. exd5 O-O $11 {if someone can apply pressure here, it's got to be Black. The g7-bishop looks dangerous.}) 11... Nxe5 {the point behind an early ...Nbd7.} 12. Bxe5 O-O {you can even stop memorizing here. Black keeps a healthy position once their king is safe. Here are a few sample lines for you.} 13. f4 $5 {trying to open up the board.} (13. Qc2 {[%csl Ge4] defending e4. This prevents ...b4.} Nd7 {forcing the bishop trade.} 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. f4 (15. e5 f5 $5 $132) 15... f6 16. e5 f5 $132 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd7b6,Gb5b4,Gd8d4] with an incredibly messy position on the board. That being said, Black's moves are flowing.}) 13... b4 $1 {releasing the tension at the right time.} 14. fxg5 hxg5 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. e5 Be7 17. Ne4 {It seems like White is dominating the board but after} c5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7h1] Black not just survives, but thrives.} 18. Nxc5 (18. dxc5 Qd5 19. Nf6+ Bxf6 20. exf6 Bb7 {[%cal Gb7d5,Gf8c8,Gc8c5] also leads to a comfortable equality.}) 18... Bxc5 19. dxc5 Bb7 20. Bxc4 Qxd1 21. Raxd1 Rac8 $11 {restoring the material balance, thus leading to an equal endgame.} *

