{In the third chapter, we'll cover the 9.Ne5 & 9.e5 in the Absolute main line of the Anti-Moscow.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 dxc4 7. e4 g5 8. Bg3 b5 {the starting point of this chapter.} 9. Ne5 {The main sideline. White wants to prevent getting hit with ...g4. They might play Be2-0-0 or just play h4 next.} (9. e5 {played by some strong players, but remains unimpressive.} Nd5 {we get a central outpost for free.} 10. Nd2 (10. Be2 Bb4 11. Rc1 Qa5 $17 {[%csl Ra2,Rc3][%cal Gd5c3,Gc4c3] We'll win the pawn on c3 soon.}) (10. h4 Qa5 11. Rc1 b4 {White has to force a queen trade here, which is clearly unfavourable for them.} 12. Qa4 Qxa4 13. Nxa4 gxh4 14. Bxh4 c3 $1 15. bxc3 bxc3 $15 {[%cal Gf8b4] Black manages to keep the extra pawn for the moment.}) 10... Qa5 (10... Bb7 $5) 11. Nde4 b4 12. Na4 c3 13. b3 Nd7 $13 {[%cal Gc8a6,Ge8c8] we'll play ...Ba6 & ...0-0-0 next. Black's moves are flowing here while they keep an extra pawn.}) (9. h4 {this is covered separately in the next chapter.}) 9... Nbd7 {offering the c6 pawn once again!} 10. Nxc6 (10. Be2 {transposes to the previous chapters.}) 10... Qb6 {Black's play starts flowing once again.} 11. d5 (11. Ne5 {This is too slow. After} Bb7 12. f3 Bg7 13. a4 a6 14. Bf2 O-O $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb5b4,Gb6d6,Rf6d7,Rg7d4] Black manages to keep a spatial edge on the Queenside. The d4-pawn remains weak while e5 or d5 doesn't seem to be a viable break for White.}) 11... Bb7 12. a4 {forcing a series of exchanges on the Queenside.} a6 13. Be2 Bxc6 14. dxc6 Qxc6 15. e5 $5 {the more widely played move.} (15. axb5 axb5 16. Rxa8+ Qxa8 {unfortunately, they cannot play 17.Nxb5 due to the threat of ...Bb4!+} 17. O-O Qb7 18. Bf3 (18. e5 Nd5 $15 {White doesn't have sufficient compensation here.}) 18... e5 $11 {[%csl Rf3,Rg3] locking down the bishops. We'll play ...Bg7/...Bc5 and ...0-0 next. Black keeps a comfortable game.}) 15... Nd5 16. Nxd5 Qxd5 17. Qxd5 exd5 18. axb5 {it seems like they end up with a better pawn structure but after} Bb4+ 19. Kd1 Nc5 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5] Black's passed pawns in the center look dangerous too.} 20. bxa6 Nxa6 21. Bf3 O-O 22. Ke2 Nc7 $11 {with a static equality on the board. White will probably liquidate with e6 at some point.} *

