{the 4th and the final chapter on the Anti-Moscow covers 9.h4 & a few other sidelines within the system.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 dxc4 {the starting point of this chapter.} 7. e4 {the usual move.} ({apart from 7.e4, there are a few other sidelines we should check out.} 7. e3 {This is inferior as Black doesn't have to weaken their Kingside with ...g5 anymore.} b5 {[%csl Gb5,Gc4,Gc6]} 8. a4 {the only way to challenge our pawns on the Queenside.} Bb4 $1 $15 {White doesn't have sufficient compensation. Normal developing moves like ...0-0-Nbd7 & ...Qb6 should be sufficient to give us an edge here.}) (7. a4 Bb4 8. e3 b5 {transposes.}) 7... g5 8. Bg3 b5 9. h4 $5 {One of the most direct moves. White provokes ...g4.} g4 10. Ne5 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Ge5g4] their point.} Nbd7 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gd7e5] as usual, we challenge the knight on e5.} 11. Be2 {is the most played move in the position.} (11. Nxc6 {grabbing the pawn as usual doesn't challenge us.} Qb6 {Black's play flows here.} 12. d5 (12. Ne5 Bb7 13. Be2 Bb4 $11) 12... Bb7 13. a4 {White's usual undermining operation on the Kingside.} a6 14. Be2 Bxc6 15. dxc6 Qxc6 16. axb5 axb5 17. Rxa8+ Qxa8 18. O-O (18. Nxb5 $6 Qa5+ 19. Nc3 Nxe4 $17) 18... Qc6 {we have managed to consolidate our Queenside.} 19. e5 Nh5 20. Bh2 {[%csl Rg4] It seems like we are under pressure due to the loose pawn on g4 but in fact, after} b4 21. Nb1 g3 22. fxg3 Ng7 23. Nd2 Nxe5 $11 {[%csl Rh2] Black's position looks aesthetically more pleasant.}) (11. Nxg4 Nxg4 {the simplest choice.} (11... Rg8 $5 {[%cal Gg8g3,Rd7f6,Rb5b4] merits attention too. Black is in fact slightly better here.}) 12. Qxg4 b4 13. Na4 Ba6 $11 {[%csl Ra4,Rd4][%cal Ga6b5,Rd8a5,Gd7f6,Gd8d4] we'll play ...Qa5 or ...Bb5 next. White has problems with their knight on a4.}) 11... Rg8 $5 {[%cal Gf6h5] This rare move is my recommendation. We don't commit to a plan. Black threatens ...Nh5.} (11... Bb7 12. Nxd7 {leads to a big main line.}) 12. Nxc6 {White claims to have the best possible piece configuration for capturing the pawn.} (12. O-O {Once they castle, we can play ...Bb7.} Bb7 13. Nxg4 (13. Nxd7 Qxd7 14. Be5 Be7 $11 {[%cal Gc6c5] we'll undermine their center with ...c5 next. b3 will be met with ...b4.}) 13... b4 14. Na4 Nxe4 15. Bxc4 h5 16. Ne3 Qf6 {time for some action on the Kingside!} 17. Qxh5 O-O-O 18. Rad1 Nxg3 19. fxg3 Qh6 $1 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gh6e3]} 20. Qf3 (20. Qxh6 Bxh6 21. Kf2 c5 $11 {[%cal Gh6e3,Gg8g3] leads to simplification.}) 20... c5 $13 {with complications. Black isn't risking much, though. White's king is a lot more vulnerable.}) (12. Nxg4 Nxg4 13. Bxg4 b4 14. Na4 Ba6 $15 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Ga6b5] Black is on top here.}) 12... Qb6 {Black doesn't still mind it as their c8-bishop is going to be hyper-active on b7.} 13. d5 $5 {trying to maintain the knight on c6.} (13. Ne5 Bb4 14. O-O Bxc3 15. bxc3 Nxe4 16. Nxd7 Bxd7 $11 {leads to comfortable equality. Black's moves are quite intuitive.}) 13... Nc5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc5e4] hitting the base of their central pawn chain.} 14. Qc2 b4 15. Na4 Nxa4 16. Qxa4 Bd7 17. Qc2 {the more ambitious response. White maintains the pawn on e4.} (17. Bxc4 {this initiates a sequence of forced moves.} Nxe4 18. O-O-O Rc8 19. dxe6 fxe6 20. Rxd7 Qxc6 21. Qxc6 Rxc6 $11 {everything liquidates.}) 17... Nh5 $5 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Gh5g3] going for their active bishop..} 18. Bh2 Bxc6 19. dxc6 b3 $1 {[%cal Gf8b4] opening up the b4-square for our bishop.} 20. axb3 (20. Qxc4 g3 $132) 20... cxb3 21. Qc4 Bb4+ 22. Kf1 g3 23. Bg1 gxf2 24. Bxf2 Ng3+ $11 {[%cal Gg3e2,Gb6c6] they either need to give up the dark-squared bishop, or the c6-pawn. Black liquidates comfortably.} *

