{In the fifth chapter, we begin our coverage of the 'Moscow' variation.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 {White doesn't give us the opportunity to play ...dxc4. Instead, they give up their bishop.} Qxf6 {Black wins the bishop pair. In return, White keeps a lead in development and somewhat extra space.} 7. Qb3 $5 {they key sideline. White discourages ...dxc4.} (7. Qc2 {[%cal Gc2c8] threatening cxd5-Nxd5.} dxc4 {taking advantage of the opportunity that the pawn can be captured!} ({also possible is the solid} 7... Bb4 $5 {leading to easy positions. Here's a sample line for you-} 8. e3 Nd7 9. a3 Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 O-O 11. Bd3 dxc4 $1 {followed by the ...e5-break or the ...b6-Bb7-c5 break.} 12. Bxc4 (12. Qxc4 e5 $11) 12... b6 $11 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gc6c5]}) 8. e3 b5 9. a4 {trying to undermine their center.} ({trying to be creative with} 9. Nxb5 cxb5 10. Qe4 {backfires. After} Bb4+ 11. Kd1 O-O $1 12. Qxa8 Bd7 $17 {[%csl Ra8]} 13. Qe4 Bc6 14. Qf4 Qd8 $19 {[%csl Rd1][%cal Gc6d5,Gd8a5,Ga5a4] White's king is busted.}) 9... Bb7 {giving back the pawn for quick development.} 10. axb5 cxb5 11. Nxb5 Bb4+ 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Bxc4 {is the only move that makes sense.} Bxf3 14. gxf3 Qxf3 15. O-O {unfortunately, there are just too many pieces that are traded off the board.} Qg4+ ({if you're ambitious, you can try} 15... Nd7 16. Qe4 Qxe4 17. Nxe4 a5 $11 {and play around for some more time.}) 16. Kh1 Qf3+ $11 {leads to a repetition.}) (7. g3 {[%csl Rc4,Gc6,Gd5][%cal Rf1g2,Rd5c4] White's bishop is generally misplaced on g2 against the ...d5-c6 configuration.} Nd7 {[%cal Gd7e5] starting out with this prevents Ne5.} 8. Bg2 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. e4 {they are hoping for a small spatial edge after ...dxe4 11.Nxe4.} dxc4 {not giving them the opportunity!} 11. e5 Qg6 12. Qe2 Qd3 {the trades soften the impact of space for Black.} 13. Qxd3 cxd3 14. Rad1 Rd8 15. Rxd3 a5 $11 {[%cal Gd7b6,Ga5a4,Rf7f6,Rg7g5] preparing ...a4 & ...Nb6. If given a chance, we would like to strike with ...c5. Black keeps a tiny strategic edge thanks to the bishop pair.}) (7. e4 {allows Black to obtain easy play.} dxe4 8. Nxe4 Bb4+ 9. Ned2 c5 $15 {once the position is opened up, the pair of bishops would reveal their true potential.}) (7. e3 {the main line of the system. This is covered in the subsequent chapters.}) 7... Qe7 {[%cal Ge7b4] threatening to meet 8.e4 with ...dxe4 9.Nxe4 Qb4+!} 8. a3 $5 {preventing ...Qb4. However, White had to waste a move for this.} (8. e3 {If they had to play this, they shouldn't have played Qb3.} g6 9. Bd3 Bg7 {Black basically gets a better version of the mainline on the board. The queen on b3 is misplaced.} 10. O-O O-O 11. Rac1 Nd7 {[%cal Gd5c4,Ge6e5] preparing ...dxc4-e5.} 12. Rfd1 dxc4 13. Bxc4 (13. Qxc4 {against this,} e5 {is quite effective as d5 runs into ...Nb6.}) 13... b6 $11 {[%csl Gc8,Gg7][%cal Gc8b7,Gc6c5] with easy play for Black.}) (8. e4 dxe4 9. Nxe4 Qb4+ {the point behind 7...Qe7!} 10. Kd1 $5 {[%cal Gb3c2] They want us to take on b3, which will help them improve the pawn structure. Otherwise, White wants to play Qc2 and keep a huge lead in development.} (10. Qxb4 Bxb4+ $15 {[%csl Gb4,Gc8]}) (10. Nc3 Qxb3 11. axb3 Nd7 {without the queens on the board, Black doesn't face any real issues provided they are able to develop comfortably.} 12. O-O-O Bb4 13. Be2 a5 14. Rhe1 Ke7 {our king remains quite safe in the center.} 15. Bf1 Rd8 $11 {[%cal Ge7f8,Gb7b6] with ...Kf8 & ...b6 coming in next}) 10... c5 {changing the nature of the position.} 11. Qxb4 $5 (11. d5 Be7 {it is white who risks ending up worse here.} 12. d6 (12. Bd3 O-O $15 {[%cal Ge6d5,Gf8d8]}) 12... f5 $1 13. dxe7 fxe4 14. Ne5 Rg8 {we will round up the pawn on e7 next.}) 11... cxb4 {[%csl Rd4] the d4-pawn remains a permanent weakness.} 12. Ne5 (12. Bd3 Be7 $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge8g8]}) 12... Be7 13. Be2 {[%cal Gh1d1,Gd1c2]} O-O 14. Kc2 a5 15. Rhd1 b6 $11 {[%cal Ga8a7,Ga7c7,Yc8b7] we want to play ...Bb7 or ...Ra7-Rc7-Bb7 next. If Black manages to develop comfortably, they will be exerting pressure here.}) (8. g3 {This was played by GM Bacrot in one of his games.} g6 {sticking to the usual plan. Black's bishop is quite strong on g7 as it exerts pressure over the pawn on d4.} (8... Qb4 {gives White the option of playing} 9. c5 {[%cal Gb4b3,Ga2b3,Ga1a8]}) 9. Bg2 Bg7 10. O-O O-O {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd5c4,Ge6e5] Black would like to play ...Nbd7-dxc4-e5 in these lines.} 11. e4 {trying to change the nature of the position.} (11. e3 dxc4 12. Qxc4 Nd7 $11 {[%cal Ge6e5] ...e5 is coming up next.}) 11... dxc4 12. Qxc4 b5 $1 {[%csl Rg2] against e4, this becomes effective as Ne5 doesn't pressurise the pawn on c6 anymore.} 13. Qd3 (13. Qb3 Nd7 14. e5 c5 $1 {sacrificing a pawn for initiative!} 15. Nxb5 Rb8 16. Qa4 Bb7 $15 {[%csl Rb2,Rb5,Rd4][%cal Gb7c6,Rb7f3,Rb8b5,Gc5d4,Gd7e5,Gb8b2] Black is exerting some serious pressure here.}) 13... b4 {[%cal Gc8a6,Ga6f1] the drawback of keeping the queen on the a6-f1 diagonal.} 14. Ne2 (14. Na4 Ba6 $17) 14... c5 $15 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7h1] The opening up of the position helps Black as they possess the bishop pair.}) 8... g6 {sticking to the usual plan.} 9. e4 $5 {White's point behind a3. They expand in the center.} (9. e3 Bg7 $11 {Black will play ...Nd7-dxc4 followed by ...e5 or ...b6-Bb7 next.}) 9... Bg7 {[%csl Rc4] we continue to focus on our development.} 10. Be2 {the most logical response.} (10. e5 $5 {the only to equalize according to the engine.} O-O 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Bd3 Nc6 $11 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6a5,Gb7b6] Despite the computer claiming this position as equal, I think in a practical game, humans would prefer being Black here.}) (10. Bd3 dxe4 11. Nxe4 f5 12. Nc3 c5 $15 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gg7a1] our bishop on g7 and the knight on b8 will now be activated.}) (10. O-O-O {runs into} dxc4 11. Qxc4 b5 $15 {[%cal Gb5b4] they risk getting attacked here.}) 10... dxc4 $1 11. Qxc4 O-O 12. O-O b6 {threatening ...Ba6/...Bb7.} 13. Rfe1 Bb7 14. Rad1 Nd7 $15 {[%cal Gc6c5,Ra7a6,Rb6b5] Black has managed to develop comfortably. Next, we want to play an immediate ...c5 or play ...a6-b5 and prepare ...c5-c4.} *

