{in the 6th chapter, we will cover the main line of the 'Moscow' system arising after 7.e3.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Qxf6 7. e3 {White strengthens their center and avoids ...dxc4.} g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gb8d7] Black sticks to the usual plan. Play ...g6-Bg7-Nbd7.} 8. Be2 {Both this & 8.Bd3 are equally popular.} (8. Bd3 {compared to the Qb3 lines, White keeps an extra tempo here.} Bg7 9. O-O O-O {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd5c4,Ge6e5,Yb7b6,Yc8b7] If they remain slow, we'll play ...Nbd7-dxc4 followed by ...e5 or ...b6-Bb7.} 10. e4 $5 {the critical test. They expand.} (10. Ne5 {can be met with the usual} dxc4 11. Bxc4 (11. Nxc4 Nd7 $11 {[%cal Gc6c5]}) 11... c5 {[%csl Re5] the drawback of having a knight on e5!} 12. f4 {This is intimidating when the center is locked in, not when it is completely open.} cxd4 13. Qxd4 (13. exd4 Rd8 $15 {[%csl Rd4]}) 13... Nd7 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf6d4] since we keep a better pawn structure, we don't mind trading.} 14. Ne4 Qd8 15. Rad1 Qa5 $11 {we threaten ...Nxe5. White needs to be careful not to end up getting worse.}) 10... Qd8 {[%cal Gc6c5] keeping flexibility for the moment. We don't commit to ...dxc4 or ...dxe4. We want to strike with ...c5 next.} 11. e5 {the most ambitious. They expand further.} (11. cxd5 exd5 {[%cal Gc8g4] the trades help us bring our bishop into the game.} 12. e5 c5 $1 {striking at the right time!} 13. dxc5 Nc6 14. Rc1 Bg4 {all of Black's pieces join the game.} (14... Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 $11 {equalises too.}) 15. Be2 {forced.} Be6 {the point behind ...Bg4 was to make sure they need to spend a tempo on moving their bishop in case they want an open e-file for their rook.} 16. Re1 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. Bf3 Bf4 $1 19. Ra1 d4 $11 {the last precise move you need to know. Black equalizes comfortably.}) 11... c5 {striking back in the center.} 12. dxc5 dxc4 13. Bxc4 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7c5,Rd7e5] hitting both the pawns simultaneously.} 14. Qe2 Nxc5 15. Rfd1 Qe7 16. Rd6 Bd7 $11 {developing comfortably. The position remains balanced. However, if White doesn't act quickly, our advantage of the bishop may transform into something tangible soon.}) (8. Rc1 {[%cal Rc4d5,Rc3d5]} Nd7 {[%cal Gd7e5] avoiding Ne5 ideas while preventing cxd5-Nxd5.} 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. O-O (10. e4 dxc4 11. Bxc4 O-O 12. O-O {transposes.}) (10. cxd5 {this trade is never challenging for us.} exd5 {Black has a great version of the QGD.} 11. O-O O-O 12. b4 {going for the minority attack.} a6 13. a4 Qd6 {preparing to meet b5 with ...axb5-c5.} 14. Qb3 Nf6 15. b5 axb5 16. axb5 c5 $132) 10... O-O 11. e4 dxc4 12. Bxc4 Qe7 {we threaten ...c5.} (12... c5 13. d5 $5) 13. e5 (13. Re1 c5 14. d5 Ne5 $11) 13... c5 14. Re1 cxd4 15. Qxd4 Nb6 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gd7c6] if we manage to play ...Bd7-Bc6, we should end up being better.} 16. Ne4 Bd7 17. Nf6+ Kh8 18. Bd3 (18. Nxd7 Nxd7 $11 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gd7e5]}) 18... Bc6 19. Be4 Rad8 $11 {[%cal Gc6e4,Gb6d5] we'll take on e4 and play ...Nd5 next. The e5-pawn would then be a target.}) (8. Ne5 {one of the most ambitious moves in the position.} Bg7 9. f4 {they are gaining as much space as they can.} O-O 10. h4 {going for the kill on the Kingside!} ({a slow move like} 10. Bd3 {is ineffective. After} c5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc5d4] their center becomes vulnerable.} 11. dxc5 $6 Nd7 $15 {[%csl Ra1,Rc4,Rc5,Re3][%cal Gg7a1]}) 10... Qe7 {we don't care! They cannot mate us with just two pieces :)} 11. g4 $5 {continuing to expand.} (11. h5 $6 {this isn't scary and can be parried away comfortably with} g5 {White's attack isn't going anywhere. They get hammered on the dark squares.} 12. Qd2 gxf4 13. exf4 Nd7 14. O-O-O Nxe5 15. dxe5 f6 $15 {our bishop on g7 will be unchallengable.}) (11. Qc2 c5 12. O-O-O Nc6 $132 {[%csl Rc4,Rd4][%cal Rh4h5,Rg6g5,Ge7g5,Gc6e5,Ga8b8,Gb8b2,Gc8c1] our pieces join the action too. h5 will always be met with ...g5.}) 11... c5 {striking back in the center!} 12. Qd2 dxc4 13. O-O-O Nc6 14. Bg2 {this was played in the only OTB game in the variation.} (14. Bxc4 Rd8 15. h5 (15. Nxc6 bxc6) 15... Nxe5 16. fxe5 g5) 14... cxd4 15. exd4 Bd7 {[%cal Gf8d8] simply connecting the rooks.} 16. h5 {the natural expansion is the best move for White. However, after} ({after} 16. g5 h5 $17 {[%cal Gf8d8] Black was significantly better in: ½-½ (43) Indjic,A (2620)-Giri,A (2760) Chennai 2022}) 16... Nxe5 17. dxe5 Rfd8 $11 {[%csl Re5,Rf4][%cal Gd7c6,Gg6g5] Black's play is easier.}) (8. Qc2 {[%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5] playing the queen on c2 is a bit too committal. Remember that whenever the rook or queen comes to the c-file, they threaten cxd5-Nxd5.} Nd7 $1 {[%cal Ga8c8] important!} 9. Bd3 (9. Be2 Bg7 $11 {following our usual development scheme. Black will play ...0-0-Qe7 next. We'll then play ...e5 or ...b5-a6-c5 or ...b6-Bb7.}) 9... Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. Rad1 (11. Rac1 dxc4 12. Bxc4 b6 $11 {[%cal Gf6e7,Gc8b7,Re6e5,Yc6c5] the usual plans equalise comfortably.}) 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 Qe7 (12... b6 13. e4 Bb7 $11 {also equalises.}) 13. Rfe1 a6 $132 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc6c5] White cannot stop us from playing ...b5-c5.}) 8... Bg7 {sticking to the development scheme.} 9. O-O ({starting out with this doesn't change much.} 9. e4 dxe4 10. Nxe4 Qf4 {sticking to our standard response against Be2-e4. This is what we do with 0-0 0-0 included.} 11. Qc2 {here, it's important to strike in the center with} c5 $1 12. Nxc5 (12. dxc5 O-O 13. O-O {transposes.}) 12... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4]} 13. d5 Nd4 14. Nxd4 Qxd4 {Black should soon recover the pawn.} 15. Nxe6 $5 {the only interesting response.} fxe6 16. Qxg6+ Ke7 17. O-O Qf6 18. Qe4 Qd4 $11 {with a repetition to follow.}) 9... O-O 10. e4 {White expands as usual.} (10. Ne5 {can be met with the usual} c5 {striking in the center!} 11. cxd5 cxd4 12. exd4 exd5 {an open center favours Black as they possess the bishop pair.} 13. Bf3 {[%csl Rd5]} (13. f4 Nc6 14. Qd2 Be6 $11 {[%csl Rb4,Rd4][%cal Gf6e7,Ge7b4] we would like to shuffle our queen next.}) 13... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6d4] the pressure over the d4-pawn neutralises the weakness on d5.} 14. Re1 {[%cal Ge1e5]} (14. Nxd5 Qd6 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Ne3 Qxd4 $11 {liquidates into a slightly favourable endgame for Black.}) 14... Qd6 {[%cal Gg7a1] reasserting the pressure over the e5-knight.} 15. Nxf7 {played in some high-level encounters.} (15. Nb5 Qd8 16. Nc3 Qd6 {leads to a cozy repetition.} (16... Ne7 {[%cal Ge7f5,Gc8e6] there's nothing wrong in playing on as well.} 17. Qb3 Be6 18. Qxb7 Nf5 $5)) (15. Nxd5 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Bxe5 $11 {[%csl Gc8,Ge5]}) 15... Rxf7 16. Bxd5 Bf5 {[%cal Ga8g8]} 17. g4 $5 {continuing to play with enthusiasm.} (17. Bxf7+ Kxf7 18. Qb3+ Kf8 $11 {[%csl Gc6,Gf5,Gg7][%cal Ga8b8] Black's pieces are harmonious.}) 17... Bd7 18. Bxf7+ Kxf7 19. Nb5 Qf6 20. Qb3+ Kf8 21. Re3 {[%cal Ge3f3]} Na5 {it seems like this is a blunder as after} 22. Qb4+ Kg8 23. Qxa5 {White wins a piece but after} Rf8 $132 {it is now White who needs to be careful with their king!}) 10... dxe4 11. Nxe4 Qf4 {[%csl Rd4,Re4] keeping the pressure on the center.} 12. Qd3 {the best way to maintain the center. However, the queen's somewhat misplaced here.} (12. Qc2 {can be met with} c5 13. dxc5 a5 $11 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc8d7,Gd7c6,Gc6e4,Yb8a6,Ya6c5,Yf4c7] stopping b4. Black will play ...Bd7-Bc6-Na6-Nxc5. They cannot hang onto the extra pawn.}) 12... Nd7 {back to the usual developing scheme.} 13. Rad1 b6 {[%cal Gc6c5] we threaten ...c5.} 14. Qe3 (14. c5 $5 {preventing c5. This can be met with} bxc5 15. dxc5 Nf6 $11 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf6d5,Ga7a5,Gc8a6] heading for the outpost on d5.}) 14... Qxe3 15. fxe3 c5 $11 {with a somewhat easier position for Black to handle in a practical game.} *

