{With this chapter, we begin our coverage of the 'Meran' system.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 c6 5. e3 {the first point of deviation. Instead of Bg5, White plays in a more conservative fashion and avoids getting run into ...dxc4 ideas. However, in doing so, they lock down their bishop on c1.} Nbd7 {we bring our knight out nevertheless. Typically, Black brings their bishop out to d6. However, the setup I recommend is ...Nbd7-Be7 followed by playing 0-0 & ...b6 interchangeably based on White's response.} 6. Qc2 {One of the two major systems in the position. White can play this or 6.Bd3.} Be7 {The bishop is less actively placed on e7 than on d6. However, the advantage of having the bishop on e7 is that after e4 dxe4 Nxe4, the bishop on e7 isn't attacked! (unlike it would have been on d6).} 7. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2]} b6 {now that e4 isn't a threat, we can start with ...b6. Be careful with this when Bd3-e4-Nxe4-Bxe4 is a serious threat.} 8. Bb2 (8. Bd3 Bb7 9. O-O O-O {transposes to Chapter 9.}) 8... Bb7 9. Bd3 (9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O {transposes to the next chapter.}) 9... O-O 10. O-O {both sides have completed their basic developing moves. Here, I recommend playing} h6 {which reduces the effect of White's Ne5. The reason why I like this particular setup is because it is easy to remember but more importantly, White has to show restraint as their intended solution e4 isn't easy to implement on the board.} 11. Rad1 {The most widely played move. White wants to play e4 at some point.} (11. e4 $5 {this is what Black had been waiting for. After} dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 f5 $1 {[%cal Gc6c5]} 14. Bd3 c5 $132 {[%cal Gb7f3,Ge7f6] Black obtains counterplay.}) (11. Ne5 {White's usual plan in such positions.} Nxe5 {we spoil their structure.} 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. f4 Nc5 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gc5d3]} 14. Be2 {It seems like White has consolidated. Time for some action!} dxc4 $1 15. bxc4 b5 {generating play through the Queenside!} 16. cxb5 Rc8 17. a4 $5 (17. bxc6 Bxc6 {[%csl Gc5,Gc6,Re3][%cal Gd8b6,Yd8a5] we keep massive compensation.}) 17... cxb5 18. Nxb5 {here, it's important to be pre} ({including a tempo with} 18. Rfd1 {only helps Black. After} Qa5 19. Nxb5 Ne4 20. Qb3 Rfd8 $132 {[%cal Ga7a6] our compensation is evident.}) 18... a6 (18... Ne4 19. Qd3 Qxd3 20. Bxd3 a6 $11 {also equalises comfortably.}) 19. Nd4 Bd5 $44 {[%cal Ga6a5,Gc5e4] our activity speaks for itself.}) (11. Rfd1 $5 Qc7 (11... dxc4 12. bxc4 c5 13. d5 $1 $16) (11... Rc8 12. Qe2 {can be slightly annoying. They threaten Ne5.}) 12. e4 {the most natural, but ineffective.} (12. Rac1 Rfe8 $5 {staying flexible.} 13. Ne5 {What else?} dxc4 14. Bxc4 (14. Nxc4 c5 $132) 14... Rad8 $132 15. f4 Rf8 $13 {[%cal Gc7b8,Gc6c5] we'll play ...Qb8 & ...c5 next. The position contains a lot of dynamism. If we are able to trade, we should end up slightly better due to the pawn structure. White would of course look to exploit their lead in activity.}) (12. Qe2 Rad8 $11) 12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Nf6 15. Bd3 c5 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gb7f3] Black's pieces start hinting towards a kingside attack!}) (11. Rac1 {can be met with} dxc4 12. bxc4 c5 $132 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gb7f3] with great play for Black.}) 11... Qc7 {we remain flexible.} 12. Qe2 {[%cal Gf3e5] preparing Bb1-Ne5.} (12. Rfe1 Rad8 {we keep the pressure on. We are waiting for them to play e4.} 13. e4 {This is what I would expect from most players. However, after} (13. h3 $5 {such moves are not easy for most players. White keeps waiting as well.} Rfe8 14. e4 {most natural response.} (14. a3 {still waiting!} a6 {we wait too!} 15. e4 {finally!} dxe4 16. Nxe4 c5 $132 {[%cal Gb7h1] Black keeps the usual counterplay here.} 17. dxc5 Bxe4 18. Bxe4 Nxc5 $132) 14... dxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Nf6 17. Bd3 c5 $132 {Black develops thematic play here. These positions are somewhat more comfortable for Black to handle.}) (13. cxd5 cxd5 $132 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb6b5] maintains the balance.}) 13... dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Nf6 $11 {Black has managed to neutralize their pressure effectively. We threaten ...Nxe4-c5.}) 12... Rad8 {bringing all pieces into the game.} 13. Bb1 (13. Ne5 {can be met with the thematic} dxc4 $1 14. bxc4 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nd7 16. f4 Nc5 17. Bc2 Rxd1 18. Rxd1 Ba6 $132 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gc5b7,Gb7a5] White's pawn on c4 is weak.}) 13... Rfe8 {still waiting!} 14. Qc2 {[%cal Gc4d5] threatening cxd5-Nxd5!} (14. Ne5 {this leads to a series of forced moves.} dxc4 15. bxc4 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Qxe5 17. Nd5 Qb8 18. Nxe7+ Rxe7 19. Be5 Qc8 {White has compensation, but nothing more.} 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. Qg4+ Kh8 22. Qh4 Kg7 $11) (14. h3 Bd6 {this time, we finally improve our bishop as e4 isn't a threat anymore!} 15. Rfe1 Ba6 $1 16. Bd3 Qc8 17. e4 dxc4 18. Bxc4 Bxc4 19. Qxc4 b5 20. Qd3 e5 $132 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gc6c5] with a rich strategic middlegame on the board. Black wants to play ...a6 & ...c5 next.}) (14. cxd5 exd5 $1 (14... cxd5 15. Ne5 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) 15. Ne5 Qc8 $5 {[%cal Gb7a6,Ge7d6] we'll play ...Ba6 & ...Bd6 next. If they play f4, it would weaken the e4-square. We can then play ...Bb4.}) 14... Bd6 {[%cal Gd6c7] keeping the queen guarded!} 15. h3 $5 {playing a game of restraint.} (15. e4 dxe4 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Nf8 {[%cal Gc6c5] ...c5 is up on the cards.} 18. Qg4 {the only way to prevent c5.} f5 $1 19. Qh5 Qf7 {generating play from the other flank this time.} 20. Qxf7+ Kxf7 $132 {[%cal Gc6c5,Rg7g5] we'll play ...c5 or ...g5 next.}) (15. Rfe1 {should be finally be met with} e5 {this time, we strike first!} 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 $11 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Ge5h2,Ge5c3,Gf6e4] threatening Bxc3-Nxe4 or ...dxc4.}) 15... Ba6 {forcing them to either move their knight back or finally play e4.} 16. e4 {Nd2 would have been too passive.} dxe4 {starting a sequence of forced moves.} 17. Nxe4 Nxe4 18. Qxe4 Nf8 19. Rfe1 f6 $132 {[%cal Gc6c5] keeping everything guarded. Next, we'll play ...c5. Black wants to trade pieces and go into an endgame. Once sufficient pieces are traded, you can think of playing ...e5 and expand. The endgames would be favourable for Black due to their central mobility of pawns.} *

