{In the eighth chapter, we'll cover some miscellaneous setups arising with Bd3-Qc2-b3.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 c6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Bd3 {against this move order, we play ...Be7 & ...0-0 first.} Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Qc2 b6 {the starting point of this chapter.} 9. e4 $5 {They want to take advantage of our move order.} (9. cxd5 {almost everytime, we want to meet this with} cxd5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ga7a6,Ge7d6]} 10. Bd2 Bb7 11. Rac1 a6 $11 {our usual setup. Black will play ...Bd6 & ...Qe7 next. If they play Ne2, we'll play ...Ne4.}) 9... dxe4 10. Nxe4 Bb7 {[%cal Gc6c5] Black is all set to play ...c5 again!} 11. Bf4 (11. Rd1 Qc7 12. c5 {trying to desperately shut down ...c5.} h6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gb6c5] threatening ...Nxe4-bxc5.} 13. Nxf6+ Nxf6 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gb7a6] next, we want to play ...a5-a4 or ...Ba6.} 14. Bd2 (14. a3 a5 15. Bd2 Ba6 $11 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5]}) 14... a5 15. Rac1 bxc5 16. dxc5 Rfd8 17. Be2 Nd5 {[%cal Ga5a4,Gb7a6] Black keeps easy play. The other bishop can come out to f6.}) (11. Nxf6+ Nxf6 {this trade doesn't change much.} 12. c5 (12. Rd1 Qc7 13. c5 h6 {transposes.}) 12... h6 13. Be3 Qc8 $11 {[%cal Gb7a6] Black will now play on the light squares. We get the d5-outpost for our knight.}) 11... c5 12. Rad1 {White's point. They develop their pieces to the most active squares.} Nh5 {deflecting the bishop from the active diagonal.} 13. Be3 cxd4 14. Nxd4 {here, I recommend} Qb8 {[%cal Gh5f4] threatening ...Nf4.} 15. Ng5 {here, I recommend the novel} (15. Bg5 Bxg5 16. Nxg5 h6 $11 {White needs to be the one who needs to force matters here. Black has the desirable pawn structure.}) 15... g6 $5 {to keep more fighting chances Black threatens ...Nf4.} (15... h6 {is also possible. After} 16. Ngxe6 fxe6 17. Nxe6 Ndf6 18. Nxf8 Ng4 19. Bh7+ Kxf8 20. Qf5+ Nhf6 21. Bf4 Qe8 22. Bg6 Qc6 23. f3 Qxc4 $11 {[%cal Ge7c5,Gg4f2] we have a complicated repetition on the board.}) 16. Ngxe6 Re8 17. Ng5 Ndf6 {Black loses a pawn but generates attack on the Kingside. A possible line is} 18. Be2 (18. h3 Nf4 $132) 18... Bd6 19. g3 Bxg3 $1 20. hxg3 Nxg3 21. Bf3 Nxf1 22. Kxf1 h6 $44 {with good practical chances to play for a win.} *

