{In the 10th chapter, we will cover options for White where they don't opt for the main line with Bd3-b3-Qc2-Bb2.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 c6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Bd3 Be7 7. O-O O-O {the starting point of this chapter.} 8. b3 (8. e4 {starting out with this is premature as usual. After} dxe4 9. Nxe4 c5 10. Nxc5 Nxc5 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 b6 {Black keeps a somewhat easier game due to the mobile pawn structure in the center. Trade pieces and head into the endgame.}) (8. Qe2 {can be met with} dxc4 9. Bxc4 b5 $1 {when their queen is not on c2, ...b4-c5 becomes a strong option.} 10. Bd3 b4 11. Na4 c5 $11) (8. Re1 dxc4 9. Bxc4 b5 {going for the same plan. We'll play ...b4 & ...c5 next.} 10. Bd3 b4 11. Na4 c5 $11 {Black equalises comfortably.}) (8. a3 {[%cal Ga3b4] preventing ...b5-b4.} b6 {this time, we claim that Black has an improvised version of the ...b6 lines. White's a3 isn't super useful.} 9. b4 {they gain space on the Queenside.} Ba6 {[%csl Rc4,Rd3][%cal Ga6d3] going for the thematic bishop swap.} 10. c5 (10. b5 dxc4 $15) (10. Qe2 dxc4 11. Bxc4 Bxc4 12. Qxc4 b5 $1 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gc8c3]} 13. Qb3 a5 {[%csl Ra3,Rb4] white's pawn on b4 is a fixed weakness.}) 10... Bxd3 11. Qxd3 bxc5 12. bxc5 e5 $11 {...e4 is coming up next. If they take on e5, c5 becomes weak.}) 8... b6 9. Bb2 Bb7 10. Qe2 $5 {the main line of this chapter. White doesn't spend time playing Qc2 and instead moves their queen out to a better square.} (10. Qc2 h6 {transposes to the main line of the text.}) (10. e4 {is premature as usual. After} dxe4 11. Nxe4 c5 {[%cal Gb7f3] Black obtains the fighting position they were longing for.} 12. Qe2 cxd4 13. Nxd4 Nc5 $11 {the more pieces get exchanged, the easier the game gets for Black.}) (10. Rc1 {this time, I recommend transforming the structure with} dxc4 11. bxc4 (11. Bxc4 c5 $11 {leads to an equal but not a drawn endgame.}) 11... c5 {transforming the pawn structure.} 12. Qe2 (12. d5 {leads to a series of forced moves.} exd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. cxd5 Bxd5 15. Bxh7+ Kxh7 16. Qxd5 Bf6 $11 {we end up with a protected passed pawn. Of course, White has dynamic elements in their favour. However, if we reach an endgame, we might keep more chances.}) 12... Qb8 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gb8f4] a clever move. The idea is to play ...cxd4 exd4 Qf4.} 13. Rfd1 cxd4 14. exd4 Qf4 $132 {with a sharp battle on the board. White keeps more space but their pawns are more vulnerable.}) 10... Qc7 {we remain consistent with our setup.} 11. Rfd1 (11. Rac1 {since the d5-square cannot be attacked anymore by White's rook, we can play} dxc4 12. bxc4 c5 $132 {with the usual hanging pawn position arising on the board.}) (11. e4 {is met with thematic} dxe4 12. Nxe4 c5 $132) 11... Rad8 12. Rac1 Rfe8 {we wait for them to commit to something.} 13. Bb1 $5 (13. Ne5 {is met with the thematic} Nxe5 14. dxe5 dxc4 15. bxc4 Nd7 16. f4 Nc5 17. Bc2 g6 $132 {[%cal Gb7a6,Yc5b7,Yb7a5,Gd8d7,Ge8d8] ...Ba6 is coming up next. We have an imbalanced pawn structure on the board.}) (13. e4 {is met with the thematic} dxe4 14. Nxe4 c5 $1 $11) (13. a3 dxc4 14. bxc4 c5 $11) 13... dxc4 14. bxc4 c5 15. d5 {Although they have managed to get d5 in this time, the position is far from simple.} exd5 16. Nxd5 (16. cxd5 a6 {[%cal Gb6b5]} 17. a4 Bd6 $132 {[%cal Gd7f8,Gf8g6]}) 16... Nxd5 17. cxd5 Bf6 18. Qc2 g6 {Black also enjoys a protected passed pawn.} 19. Bc3 Ne5 20. Nxe5 Bxe5 21. Bxe5 Qxe5 22. e4 f5 $132 {undermining their center. We will build a fortress on the dark squares. The position remains sharp and all three results are possible.} *

