{[%evp 0,30,25,13,18,4,30,29,16,8,38,9,18,-2,-11,-9,0,4,-9,-10,7,2,-1,24,24,10,19,52,49,41,41,39,45] In the 12th chapter, we will cover the 5.g3 variation for White in the Semi-Slav.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Ge1g1] going for the maximalist strategy. They want to bring all of their pieces to the best possible squares.} Nbd7 {avoiding all Ne5 ideas.} 6. Bg2 ({another option for White is to start out with} 6. Qd3 {whenever they play, watch out for ...Ba6 tricks.} a5 7. Bg2 b6 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gc8a6,Gf8e7] preparing ...Ba6.} 8. O-O Ba6 9. b3 {forced.} Be7 10. Rd1 (10. e4 $6 b5 $1 $15 {[%csl Rc4,Re4][%cal Ga6f1] White cannot hang on their center for long!}) 10... O-O $11 {[%csl Rb3,Rc4][%cal Ga5a4,Yb6b5] we might play ...a4 or ...b5 next.}) 6... dxc4 {the drawback of their setup. We can just grab their pawn!} 7. O-O (7. a4 Be7 8. O-O {transposes.}) 7... Be7 {sticking to the usual setup. White has two decent options here.} 8. a4 {preventing ...b5.} (8. e4 {building a massive center.} O-O 9. Bf4 {White continues to play in an ambitious way. They want to meet ...b5 with d5. Here, I recommend the novel} b6 $5 {solving all of our opening problems.} 10. d5 {the most natural response.} (10. a4 a5 11. Qe2 Ba6 12. Rfd1 Bb4 13. Nd2 b5 {[%cal Gd8e8,Ge6e5] This solves all of our problems.} 14. axb5 Bxb5 15. g4 (15. Bg5 h6 $15) 15... Nb6 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gf6d7] we'll fight for the ...e5-break here. White needs to be careful not to run into ...e5.}) 10... cxd5 11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. Qxd5 Ba6 14. Nd4 Nc5 {an important move!} 15. Nc6 (15. Qxa8 Qxa8 16. Bxa8 Rxa8 $44 {[%csl Ga7,Gb6,Gc4][%cal Ge7f6] we keep sufficient compensation here.}) 15... Bb7 16. Qxc4 Qe8 $11 {after the piece swaps on e7 & b7, we equalise comfortably.}) 8... O-O 9. e4 {they want to build a massive center.} (9. a5 {trying to discourage ...b5.} b5 {we still stick to our setup nevertheless.} 10. axb6 Qxb6 11. e4 a5 {[%cal Gc8a6] we want to defend c4 at all costs.} 12. Qe2 Ba6 13. Rd1 Bb4 14. h4 Rae8 {[%cal Gc6c5]} 15. Bf4 h6 $132 {Black will play ...c5 next. Once the center is undermined, our pieces would start jumping around.}) (9. Nd2 $6 {runs into} e5 $15) (9. Qc2 a5 10. e4 {here, I recommend eliminating their spatial advantage with} e5 11. dxe5 Ng4 12. e6 fxe6 13. Qe2 Nge5 $11 {[%cal Ge7c5,Ge5d3] leading to a dynamic equality after ...Bc5 or ...Nd3.}) 9... b5 $1 {[%csl Rb5,Re4] we give back the pawn to create a bind on the light-squares.} 10. axb5 cxb5 11. e5 $5 {played in all OTB games so far.} (11. Nxb5 {can be met with} Bb7 $1 {forcing them to concede the d5-square.} 12. e5 Nd5 {[%csl Rb5,Gb7,Gd5,Gd7,Re4][%cal Yd7b6,Yd8b6]} 13. Nd2 N7b6 14. Ne4 Bc6 15. Nbc3 a5 $132 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Rd1g4,Rf7f5,Yg8h8,Yd8e8] Black keeps sufficient counterplay on the Queenside. If they play Qg4, play ...Kh8-Qe8-f5 and strike on the Kingside too.}) 11... Nd5 12. Nxb5 Qb6 13. Nc3 Bb7 $11 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gf8c8,Yd5b4,Yb4d3] Black keeps an easy game thanks to their domination of light-squares. We'll play ...a5-Rfc8 next.} *

