{In the 13th chapter, we'll will cover 5.cxd5.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c6 5. cxd5 {White goes for an immediate transformation into the QGD.} exd5 {[%cal Gc8f5] in these structures, we are glad to swap our light-squared bishops.} 6. Bf4 {[%cal Gf4c7] White's main move. They bring their bishop out of the pawn chain while covering the c7-square. This way, they can play Qb3 in many situations.} (6. Qc2 {they want to prevent ...Bf5.} g6 {fortunately for us, we can still prepare ...Bf5!} 7. h3 $5 {[%cal Rc8f5,Rg2g4,Rc2b3] preparing to meet ...Bf5 with Qb3 & g4.} (7. e3 Bf5 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Bd6 $15 {[%csl Rc1,Re4][%cal Ge8g8,Gb8d7,Gd8e7,Gf6e4] their bishop is tied down on c1.}) 7... Qc7 $5 {we prevent their Bf4. We'll ...Bf5 now.} 8. Bg5 {the most logical move. They bring their bishop out of the pawn chain.} (8. g3 {[%cal Gc1f4] while they get to play Bf4 here, they'll have to play Bg2 in this QGD structure, which is sub-optimal.} Bg7 9. Bf4 Qe7 10. Bg2 O-O 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Rfe1 Re8 13. Rad1 Nb6 $11 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gb6c4,Gf6e4,Yc8f5,Ga7a5] our pieces jump onto the central squares.}) (8. g4 $6 h5 9. g5 Bf5 10. Qb3 Nfd7 11. Bg2 Nb6 $11 {[%csl Rg5,Rh3][%cal Gb8d7,Gb7c4,Gf8e7] they have over-expanded their Kingside pawns.}) 8... Bf5 {now we can get our bishop out comfortably.} 9. Qb3 Nbd7 10. e3 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Rg2g4,Rg5f4] here, I prefer to play} (10. g4 Be6 $15 {[%cal Gh7h5] ...h5 is coming up next.}) 10... Ne4 {liquidating immediately.} 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Bf4 Bd6 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 {with extremely fluid play for Black.} 14. Nd2 Nf6 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Bd3 f5 17. Qxb7 {this initiates a sequence of forced moves with} (17. O-O Qe7 $11 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ge7b7] we equalize our comfortably here. There's no way they can attack our weaknesses. Bxe4 will be met with ...fxe4.}) 17... Rb8 18. Qg7 Qb4+ 19. Kf1 Qxb2 20. Qxh8+ Kf7 21. Qxh7+ Kf8 $11 {there's nothing better than a perpetual here.}) (6. e3 {this isn't generally impressive here.} Bd6 {[%csl Gh2][%cal Gd6h2] our bishop is quite actively placed on d6, while their bishop is stuck.} 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O Re8 {[%cal Gf6e4]} 9. Qc2 Qe7 $11 {[%cal Gf6e4] we will play ...Ne4 next. If they play Nd2, their pieces would be extremely passively placed.}) (6. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2] As mentioned earlier, the bishop really doesn't belong to the g2-square here.} h6 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf5h7]} 7. Bg2 Bf5 8. O-O Be7 $11 {with a Reversed London on the board. We keep a stable center and thus, a stable game.}) (6. Bg5 {the combination of cxd5 & Bg5 isn't promising.} h6 7. Bh4 {If Black's able to trade the light-squared bishop in the Carlsbad structure, as a rule of thumb, they shouldn't face any issues in the opening.} Bf5 8. e3 (8. Qb3 g5 9. Bg3 Qb6 $11 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Gb8d7,Rb3b6,Ra7b6,Rf6h5] we are happy to swap on b6 as we can then play ...axb6-b5.}) 8... Nbd7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Be7 {these positions are quite harmless.} 11. O-O O-O 12. Rab1 a5 13. a3 Re8 $11 {[%cal Ge7d6,Gd8c7,Rf6e4] we can prepare ...Ne4. If they play b4, watch out for ...axb4 axb4 Nb6-Nc4 (perhaps with ...b5 included) jumps.}) 6... Be7 {we develop naturally. Next, we want to play ...Bf5.} 7. e3 (7. h3 Bf5 {sticking to the plan.} 8. g4 (8. e3 {this is a bit too slow.} Qb6 9. Qc1 {[%csl Rc1]} (9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 $11 {[%cal Gf6e4] Black has the favourable version of the Carlsbad as the light-squared bishops are traded.}) 9... Nbd7 10. Be2 h6 $11 {vacating the h7-square for our bishop. We have solved our opening problems.}) 8... Bg6 {here, they have two interesting ideas.} 9. Ne5 {going for our bishop.} (9. Qb3 {is met with the usual} Qb6 10. e3 Nbd7 11. Nh4 $5 {forcing us to trade to b3.} (11. Bg2 Ne4 $15) 11... Qxb3 12. axb3 Bc2 {[%csl Rb3,Rh4][%cal Rh4f3,Rf3d2] their knight on h4 is now misplaced. They cannot play Rc1 anymore.} 13. Nf5 Bxf5 14. gxf5 g6 $11 {[%csl Rb3,Gf1,Gf4] White enjoys the advantage of bishop pair, but we keep a much better pawn structure.}) 9... Nbd7 10. Nxg6 hxg6 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Gh8h3]} 11. e3 Nf8 {[%cal Gf8e6,Gd8b6] our setup is ...Ne6 & ...Qb6.} 12. Qb3 Qb6 13. f3 Ne6 14. Bg3 Qxb3 15. axb3 a6 $132 {[%cal Gc6c5] this was played in ½-½ (64) Ponomariov,R (2647)-Fressinet,L (2637) Chess.com INT 2024. Black will undermine the center with ...c5 next and keep a comfortable game.}) (7. Qc2 {is met with the usual} g6 {[%cal Gc8f5] preparing ...Bf5.} 8. e3 (8. h3 {can be met with the thematic} Bf5 9. Qb3 Qb6 {now, if given a chance, we'll play ...h5.} 10. g4 {the last chance to get this in.} Qxb3 11. axb3 Bc2 {[%cal Ra1a8] White has to play the precise} 12. Rc1 {to kick our bishop.} (12. Bg2 Na6 13. O-O Nb4 $11 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gh7h5]}) 12... Be4 $1 {[%csl Rc1] it seems like we have lost a tempo but in fact, we have managed to move their active rook on a1 away from the open-file!} (12... Bxb3 $2 13. Nd2 $16) 13. Bg2 Nbd7 14. O-O a5 $11) 8... Bf5 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 {once these bishops are traded, Black's play becomes easy.} 11. h4 $5 {the choice of Magnus. This discourages h5.} (11. O-O O-O $11 {[%cal Ga7a5,Gf8e8,Ge7f8] we'll play ...Re8-Bf8 preparing ...Ne4 or ...a5 (stopping b4) next.}) 11... a5 {we start expanding on the other flank!} 12. Kf1 a4 13. a3 O-O {the right time to castle! They have played Kf1 this time.} 14. g3 Nb6 $1 {[%cal Gd8c8,Gc8e6] vacating the c8-h1 diagonal and heading for the c4-square.} 15. Kg2 (15. Ne5 Qc8 16. Kg2 Qe6 $11 {[%cal Gf6d7,Rb6c4] we'll neutralise their knight ...Nfd7 next.}) 15... Qc8 16. Bg5 (16. Ne5 {transposes.}) 16... h5 {stopping all expansion ideas.} 17. Ne5 Kg7 18. f3 Qe6 19. Rhe1 Nfd7 $11 {with a balanced & healthy position on the board.}) 7... Nh5 {[%csl Rf4] going for their active bishop!} 8. h3 (8. Be5 {this looks dangerous, but really isn't.} Nd7 9. Qc2 Nxe5 {going for the kill!} 10. dxe5 (10. Nxe5 Bd6 11. Bd3 g6 12. O-O-O Be6 13. f4 f6 14. Nf3 Ng7 $11 {[%csl Gd6,Re3,Ge6][%cal Gd8c7,Ge8c8] our king will be quite safe on the Queenside.}) 10... O-O 11. O-O-O g6 12. Kb1 (12. e4 Bg4 13. exd5 cxd5 $15 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gb8c8,Gc8c1,Gg4f5] White will face issues on the c-file.}) 12... b5 13. Be2 Ng7 14. h4 h5 $1 $132 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gd8b6,Ra7a5] It's us who will generate more play around the king here.}) 8... Nxf4 9. exf4 {[%csl Gc8,Ge7] it is us who now enjoy the advantage of the bishop pair.} O-O {the more precise move.} (9... Bd6 $6 10. g3 {this move helps White. After} Nd7 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Kf1 Re8 13. Kg2 $14 {[%csl Rd7] They are slightly better as our knight is misplaced.}) 10. Bd3 Na6 $1 {[%cal Ga6c7,Ge7d6,Gd8f6,Gc6c5,Rc7d5] looking to play ...Nc7-e8-g7/d6 in!} 11. Rc1 $5 (11. Bxa6 bxa6 {[%csl Gc8,Ge7]} 12. Ne5 Qe8 13. O-O f6 14. Nd3 Qg6 15. Qf3 Bf5 $11 {[%cal Ga8b8] Our pair of bishops compensate for the ruptured pawn structure.}) (11. O-O {can be met with} Nc7 $11 {[%cal Yc7e8,Ye8d6,Yc8f5,Rg7g6] followed by ...Ne8-g6-Nd6/...Ng7-Bf5.}) 11... Nc7 12. O-O Ne8 {[%cal Gg7g6]} 13. Qd2 g6 14. Rfe1 Ng7 $11 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf8e8,Ye7f8] we'll finally trade their active light-squared bishops and keep an easy game.} *

