1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c6 5. Qd3 {defending c4. They want to play e4 at some point.} (5. Bf4 {playing this without cxd5 is weak.} dxc4 6. a4 {preventing ...b5.} (6. e3 b5 $15 {[%csl Gb5,Gc4,Gc6][%cal Gf8b4] we expand on the Queenside and keep our pawn structure intact.}) 6... Bb4 $1 $15 {[%cal Gf6d5,Gb7b5] we'll play ...Nd5 or ...b5 next.}) (5. Qb3 {one of the two main lines in the position. They bring in the queen to defend the pawn.} Be7 {they can choose between two decent options here.} 6. Bg5 {the most widely played move. Here, I recommend} (6. g3 O-O 7. Bg2 Nbd7 8. O-O a5 {we start expanding on the flank. Black threatens ...a4.} 9. a4 (9. cxd5 exd5 $15) (9. Nd2 a4 $1 10. Nxa4 dxc4 {[%cal Gb7b5] preparing ...b5 next.} 11. Qc2 (11. Nxc4 $4 b5 $19) 11... b5 12. Nc3 Nd5 $11 {Black keeps an easier game here.}) (9. Bf4 a4 10. Nxa4 dxc4 {[%cal Gf6d5,Gb7b5] is quite similiar to 9.Nd2.}) 9... Qb6 {[%csl Rb4]} 10. Qc2 Qa6 $15 {they have huge holes on the Queenside. c5 will be met with ...b6, cxd5 exd5 is a favourable trade for us.}) (6. Bf4 dxc4 7. Qxc4 O-O 8. e3 (8. e4 b5 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gb5b4,Gc6c5,Yd8a5] ...b4-Qa5 or ...Ba6 is coming up next.}) 8... Nd5 $1 9. Bg3 Qb6 10. Qe2 c5 $11 {[%csl Re2,Rf1] their queen and bishop on f1 are awkwardly placed.}) 6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 b5 {[%csl Rd4] White has problems with their center/knight on c3.} 8. Qd3 (8. Qb3 Nbd7 9. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2]} (9. e3 a6 {[%csl Ga6,Gb5][%cal Gc6c5] they cannot stop ...c5 from coming up next.}) 9... b4 {a big problem for White in these lines is the ...b4-break.} 10. Na4 (10. Bxf6 Nxf6 11. Na4 Nd7 12. Bg2 Ba6 $11 {[%csl Ra4,Rb3][%cal Ga6b5,Gd8a5] the knight on a4 is awkwardly placed.}) 10... Qa5 11. Bg2 O-O 12. O-O Ba6 13. Rfe1 Bb5 14. Nc5 Nxc5 15. dxc5 Bxc5 16. Bxf6 gxf6 $11 {[%csl Gc5] It is White who needs to be a bit more precise to equalize here. Our king is under no real danger.}) 8... Nbd7 9. e4 b4 10. Na4 h6 {asking them to give up their bishop.} 11. Bxf6 (11. Bh4 {this is weaker.} O-O 12. Rc1 (12. Be2 Qa5 13. b3 c5 $15) 12... Qa5 13. b3 Bb7 14. e5 Nd5 15. Bxe7 Nxe7 16. Be2 c5 $15 {[%csl Ra2][%cal Ga8c8,Gb7f3,Rd7e5,Ra5a2] White cannot hang on to all of their weaknesses! Black's able to undermine their center.}) 11... Bxf6 12. Rc1 Bb7 13. Be2 O-O 14. O-O Be7 $11 {[%cal Gd8a5] we'll play ...Qa5. If given a chance, we would love to play ...c5.}) (5. Qc2 $5 {here, I recommend the thematic} dxc4 {going for the pawn.} 6. e4 (6. e3 {can be met with} b5 7. a4 Qb6 $15 {[%csl Gb5,Gc4,Gc6] we stabilise our pawn structure in the Queenside.}) (6. a4 {can be met with} c5 7. dxc5 Bxc5 $11 {[%cal Gb8c6,Ge8g8,Yb7b6,Yc8b7,Re6e5] the queen on c2 and the pawn on a4 are not ideal together.}) 6... b5 {we stabilise our pawn structure on the Queenside.} 7. Be2 (7. Bg5 Be7 $15 {[%csl Gb5,Gc4,Gc6] they cannot challenge our pawn.}) (7. a4 {can be met with} a6 {[%csl Ga6,Gb5,Gc4,Gc6] stabilising the Queenside.} 8. Be2 (8. axb5 $6 {this is too much. After} cxb5 9. Nxb5 axb5 10. Rxa8 Bb7 11. Ra1 Nxe4 $19 {White is busted.}) 8... Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 $15 {[%cal Gc6c5,Yb5b4] we'll want to play ...b4 & ...c5 next.}) 7... Bb7 8. O-O Be7 {here, there are a few critical moves.} 9. Rb1 {preparing b3 b4 bxc4.} (9. b3 {this is met with the thematic} b4 10. Na4 c3 {[%csl Gb4,Gc3] stabilising the Queenside. a3 will be met with ...a5. A possible line is} 11. Nc5 Qc8 12. a3 a5 13. Be3 O-O $15 {[%cal Gb8d7] Black keeps a healthy edge.}) (9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 Nbd7 11. b3 cxb3 12. axb3 O-O $15 {they don't have sufficient compensation.}) 9... Qc7 {guarding our bishop.} (9... O-O 10. b3 b4 11. bxc4 $5) 10. e5 {change of plans for White!} Nd5 11. Bg5 O-O 12. Ne4 {here, I recommend the novel} (12. b3 {can now be met with} Nxc3 13. Qxc3 Bxg5 14. Nxg5 c5 15. dxc5 h6 16. Nf3 a5 17. bxc4 b4 18. Qe3 Na6 $15 {[%csl Ga5,Gb4][%cal Ga6c5,Gb7f3] Black restores the material balance while keeping more space on the Queenside.}) 12... c5 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Nxc5 (14. dxc5 Nb4 $19 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb7e4] oops!}) 14... Bc6 15. Qd2 (15. b3 c3 $17) 15... Nb6 16. b3 N8d7 $15 {Black has complete control of the light squares on the board.}) (5. a3 {just wastes a tempo. After} dxc4 6. e4 b5 $15 {White doesn't have sufficient compensation for the lost pawn.}) (5. c5 {the expansion is premature.} b6 6. b4 a5 $17 {they cannot create a Queenside bind. We'll undermine their structure.}) (5. b3 $6 {this is a bit premature. After} Ne4 {[%csl Rc3,Re1][%cal Gf8b4,Gb4e1] they have a lot of problems around their dark squares.} 6. Bd2 Nxd2 7. Qxd2 Qa5 $15 {we win the pair of bishops and thus, keep a comfortable game.}) (5. a4 {all this does is that it weakens the b4-square.} Bb4 {[%csl Gb4] occupying the outpost.} 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c5 $1 {we now strike back in the center. After} 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 cxd4 10. exd4 Nc6 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bh4 Be7 $11 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Gc6b4] we have a favourable version of the IQP.}) (5. Ne5 Nbd7 {the knight trade doesn't help White.} 6. e3 Nxe5 7. dxe5 Nd7 8. f4 a5 {[%cal Gd5c4,Gb7b5]} 9. Be2 dxc4 10. a4 (10. Bxc4 b5 $15) 10... Bb4 11. O-O Nc5 12. Qc2 b5 13. axb5 Bxc3 $132 {[%cal Gc6b5]}) (5. Bd2 $5 Nbd7 6. e3 {transposes to the Meran lines..}) 5... Be7 6. e4 {expanding in the center. This is too ambitious.} (6. Bg5 dxc4 7. Qxc4 b5 {transposes.}) (6. g3 {the combination of Qd3 & g3 isn't challenging.} b6 {[%csl Rc4,Rd3][%cal Gc8a6,Ga6d3]} 7. Bg2 (7. cxd5 cxd5 8. Bg5 Ba6 $11) 7... Ba6 8. b3 b5 {undermining their queenside!} 9. cxb5 cxb5 10. Qe3 (10. Nxb5 $6 Qa5+ {wins material.}) 10... Nbd7 $15 {we keep more space on the Queenside.}) 6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 b5 {we start hitting them with tempos.} 8. Qd3 b4 9. Na4 Qa5 {winning a lot of tempos.} 10. b3 Ba6 {all of our moves come with a tempo.} 11. Qc2 Bxf1 12. Kxf1 Nbd7 {[%csl Rf1] they cannot castle anymore.} 13. g3 (13. Qxc6 $6 {is too ambitious. After} O-O 14. Qc2 Qa6+ 15. Qe2 Qxe2+ 16. Kxe2 Nxe4 {Black is the one applying pressure.}) (13. Bg5 {runs into} Nxe4 14. Qxc6 Qd5 15. Qxd5 exd5 $11) 13... c5 14. Kg2 O-O $11 {we eliminated our weakness and kept our king out of harm's way.} *

